135\n|-\n|9\n| [[Stop & Shop]]\n|132\n|-\n|10\n| TOMZ \n|101\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Luann de Lesseps]] (1965-), cast member on ''The Real Housewives of New York City''\n* [[Sam McKinniss]] (1985-), abstract and figurative postmodern painter; born in Minnesota, raised in Berlin from age 1\n* [[Simeon North]] (1765\u20131852), manufacturing pioneer; adopted milling/manufacturing with interchangeable parts\n* [[Ryan Preece]] (1990-), [[NASCAR]] driver \n* [[Edward Savio]] (1963-), screenwriter and novelist (''[[Idiots in the Machine]]'' and others)\n* [[Austin Stowell]] (1984-), actor known for films ''Dolphin Tale'', ''Whiplash'', and ''Bridge of Spies''\n* [[Emma Hart Willard]] (1787\u20131870), pioneer in women's education\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:PostcardBerlinCTLibrary1911.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Library, about 1911]]\nThere are three elementary schools, [[Mary E. Griswold School]], [[Emma Hart Willard School]], and [[Richard D. Hubbard School]], as well as [[Catherine M. McGee Middle School]], and [[Berlin High School (Connecticut)|Berlin High School]]. Besides these, two private education schools in Berlin include Saint Paul School (Founded 1958) and Mooreland Hill School (Founded 1930)\n\nThe town's public library is the [[Berlin-Peck Memorial Library]] located at the Arthur B. Powers complex, the library contains an adjoining community center with publicly available meeting rooms, a gym area and a game room. Adult education classes are held here as well as meetings for civic and student groups.\n\n==Pronunciation==\nAlthough taken from the name of the Prussian capital, [[Berlin]],<ref>{{cite book|title=The Connecticut Magazine: An Illustrated Monthly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoEyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA330|year=1903|publisher=Connecticut Magazine Company|page=330}}</ref> which receives the stress in its pronunciation on the second syllable, the name of the town in Connecticut has always received the stress in its pronunciation on the first syllable, in keeping with the [[recessive accent]] usual in the pronunciation of English.  Notwithstanding this history, an [[urban legend]] now current in some quarters claims that the emphasis was changed during the [[First World War]] to differentiate the little town from the German city.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n*[http://www.town.berlin.ct.us/ Town of Berlin official website]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Berlin, Connecticut\n|North     = [[Newington, Connecticut|Newington]]\n|Northeast = [[Rocky Hill, Connecticut|Rocky Hill]]\n|East      = [[Cromwell, Connecticut|Cromwell]]\n|Southeast = [[Middletown, Connecticut|Middletown]]\n|South     = [[Meriden, Connecticut|Meriden]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Southington, Connecticut|Southington]]\n|Northwest = [[New Britain, Connecticut|New Britain]]\n}}\n\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{Hartford County, Connecticut}}\n{{Greater Hartford}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Berlin, Connecticut|*]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hartford County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1785]]\n[[Category:Towns in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Greater Hartford]]\n", "name_user": "Barkeep49", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Idiots in the Machineclosed as soft delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin,_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "Tin foil hat", "text_new": "{{short description|Hat and stereotype for conspiracy theorists}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:30C3 TinFoil-Hat.jpg|alt=|thumb|Man in a tin foil hat at the [[Chaos Communication Congress]]]]\nA '''tin foil hat''' is a [[hat]] made from one or more sheets of [[aluminium foil]], or a piece of conventional headgear lined with foil, worn in the belief or hope that it shields the [[Human brain|brain]] from threats such as [[electromagnetic field]]s, [[mind control]], and [[telepathy|mind reading]]. The notion of wearing homemade headgear for such protection has become a popular [[stereotype]] and byword for [[paranoia]], [[persecutory delusions]], and belief in [[pseudoscience]] and [[conspiracy theories]].\n\n\"[[Tin foil]]\" is a common [[misnomer]] for [[aluminium foil]]; packaging metal foil was formerly made out of [[tin]] before it was replaced with [[aluminium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/foil-metallurgy|title=Foil - metallurgy|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Origin  ==\nAn early allusion to an \"insulative electrical contrivance encircling the head during thought\" appears in the unusual 1909 [[non-fiction]] publication ''Atomic Consciousness'' <ref name=\"Bathurst1909\">{{cite book |title=Atomic Consciousness Abridgement |first=James |last=Bathurst |publisher=W. Manning, London |year=1909}}</ref> by self-proclaimed \"seer\" John Palfrey (aka \"James Bathurst\") who believed such headgear was not effective for his \"retention of thoughts and ideas\" against a supposed \"telepathic impactive impingement\".<ref name=\"Wilson2016\">{{cite magazine |title=Atomic-Consciousness |magazine=[[Fortean Times]] |date=June 2016 |first=Daniel |last=Wilson}}</ref>\n\nSome people have a belief that such hats prevent [[mind control by governments]], spies, or paranormal beings that employ [[Extrasensory perception|ESP]] or the [[microwave auditory effect]]. People in many countries who believe they are \"[[Electronic harassment|targeted individuals]]\", subject to government spying or harassment, have developed websites, conference calls, and support meetings to discuss their concerns, including the idea of protective headgear.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/10/AR2007011001399_3.html|title=Mind Games|last=Weinberger|first=Sharon|date=14 January 2007|work=Washington Post|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> Over time the term \"tin foil hat\" has become associated with [[paranoia]] and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]].<ref name=\"Crazy\">{{cite web|title=Hey Crazy--Get a New Hat |url=http://www.bostonist.com/archives/2005/11/15/hey_crazyget_a_new_hat.php |accessdate=5 April 2007 |date=15 November 2005 |publisher=Bostonist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503051428/http://www.bostonist.com/archives/2005/11/15/hey_crazyget_a_new_hat.php |archivedate=3 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== Scientific basis ==\n[[Electromagnetic radiation and health|Effects of strong electromagnetic radiation on health]] have been documented for quite some time.<ref name=\"Ref_1979\">{{cite journal |title=Neurophysiologic effects of Radiofrequency and Microwave Radiation |journal=Bulletin of the New York Academy of Medicine |volume=55 |issue=11 |first=W. R. |last=Adey |date=December 1979 |pages=1079\u20131093|pmid=295243 }}</ref> The efficiency of a metal enclosure in blocking electromagnetic radiation depends on the thickness of the foil, as dictated by the \"[[skin effect|skin depth]]\" of the conductor for a particular wave frequency range of the radiation. For half-millimetre-thick aluminum foil, radiation above about 20&nbsp;kHz (i.e., including both [[AM band|AM]] and [[FM band]]s) would be partially blocked, although aluminum foil is not sold in this thickness, so numerous layers of foil would be required to achieve this effect.<ref name=\"Jackson1998\">{{cite book |title=Classical Electrodynamics |first=John David |last=Jackson |publisher=Wiley Press |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-471-30932-1 }}</ref>\n\nA belief also exists that aluminum foil is a protective measure against the effects of [[electromagnetic radiation]] (EMR) for many unspecified EMR frequencies.{{cn|date=July 2019}} There are some allegations that EMR exposure has negative health consequences.<ref name=\"Lean2006\">{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/environment/article362557.ece |title=Electronic smog |work=The Independent |date=7 May 2006 |accessdate=9 June 2009 |location=London |first=Geoffrey |last=Lean |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517030959/http://news.independent.co.uk/environment/article362557.ece |archivedate=17 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, [[Allan H. Frey]] discovered that the [[microwave auditory effect]] (i.e., the reception of the induced sounds by radio-frequency electromagnetic signals heard as clicks and buzzes) can be blocked by a patch of [[wire mesh]] (rather than foil) placed above the [[temporal lobe]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frey|first=Allan H.|date=1962-07-01|title=Human auditory system response to modulated electromagnetic energy|url=http://jap.physiology.org/content/17/4/689|journal=Journal of Applied Physiology|language=en|volume=17|issue=4|pages=689\u2013692|issn=8750-7587|pmid=13895081|doi=10.1152/jappl.1962.17.4.689}}</ref><ref name=\"Elder & Chou 2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/bem.10163 |last1=Elder |first1=Joe A. |last2=Chou |first2=C.K. |year=2003 |title=Auditory response to pulsed radiofrequency energy |journal=Bioelectromagnetics |volume=24 |issue=S6 |pages=S162\u201373 |issn=0197-8462 |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/106565261/abstract|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121104224846/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/106565261/abstract|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-04|pmid=14628312}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe usage of a metal foil hat for protection against interference of the mind was mentioned in a science fiction short story by [[Julian Huxley]], \"[[The Tissue-Culture King]]\", first published in 1926,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MkQPztA7TTIC&pg=PA118 p. 118]</ref><ref name=\"Huxley1926\">{{cite journal|last=Huxley|first=Julian|authorlink=Julian Huxley|title=The Tissue-Culture King: A Parable of Modern Science|volume= XV|year=1925\u20131926|journal=[[The Yale Review]]|pages=479\u2013504|url=http://yalereview.yale.edu/volume-xv-1925-1926}}</ref> in which the protagonist discovers that \"caps of metal foil\" can block the effects of [[telepathy]].<ref name=\"Huxley1927\">{{cite journal|last=Huxley|first=Julian|title=The Tissue-Culture King|date= August 1927|journal=[[Amazing Stories]]|quote=Well, we had discovered that metal was relatively impervious to the telepathic effect, and had prepared for ourselves a sort of tin pulpit, behind which we could stand while conducting experiments. This, combined with caps of metal foil, enormously reduced the effects on ourselves.}}</ref>\n\nTin foil hats have appeared in such films such as ''[[Signs (film)|Signs]]'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5682464/area-51-raid-hat/|title=Area 51 Raid But Make It Fashion: It Takes a Lot to Stand Out at Alien-Themed Festival But This Guy's Tin Foil Hat Is Working|last=Lang|first=Cady|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Futurama: Into the Wild Green Yonder]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/36153/futurama-into-the-wild-green-yonder/|title=Futurama: Into The Wild Green Yonder|last=Miller III|first=Randy|date=February 1, 2009|website=[[DVD Talk]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book series ''[[Artemis Fowl]]'' by [[Eoin Colfer]] features a paranoid [[centaur]] character named Foaly, who wears a tin-foil hat to protect from mind-readers. The novel ''Idiots in the Machine'' by [[Edward Savio]] portrays a character who believes tin foil keeps harmful gamma rays away, becoming a media sensation after marketing a successful line of foil hats to Chicago.\n\nThe 2019 [[HBO]] television series ''[[Watchmen (TV series)|Watchmen]]'' features the character Wade Tillman / Looking Glass, a police officer who wears a mask made of reflective foil, and while off-duty, a cap lined in foil to protect his mind from alien psychic attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/watchmen-show-easter-eggs-episode-5/|title=Watchmen: Biggest Comic Easter Eggs in Episode 5|last=Erdmann|first=Kevin|date=November 18, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nIn 2020, an [[Uzbekistan]]i citizen tried to cross the [[Belarus]]ian-[[Lithuania]]n border illegally using aluminum foil padding of the attire and a tin foil hat, to avoid detection by [[thermographic camera]]s. It was reported that the border guards face similar violations quite regularly.<ref>[https://newgrodno.by/society/shapka-nevidimka-iz-folgi-ne-pomogla-zhitelyu-uzbekistana-nezakonno-peresech-granitsu-on-zaderzhan-litovskimi-pogranichnikami/ \u00ab\u0428\u0430\u043f\u043a\u0430-\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0430\u00bb \u0438\u0437 \u0444\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044e \u0423\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043d\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0447\u044c \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0443. \u041e\u043d \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d \u043b\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Electromagnetic hypersensitivity]]\n* [[Electromagnetic radiation and health]]\n* [[Electronic harassment]]\n* [[Electrophonic hearing]]\n* [[Electrostatic discharge materials]]\n* [[Embassy attack accusations in Cuba]] (and China)\n* [[Faraday cage]]\n* [[The Hum]]\n* [[Microwave auditory effect]]\n* [[On the Origin of the \"Influencing Machine\" in Schizophrenia]]\n* [[Sonic weapon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|Tin foil hats}}\n\n{{Hats}}\n{{Pseudoscience|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tin Foil Hat}}\n[[Category:Hats]]\n[[Category:Mind control]]\n[[Category:Paranoia]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Pejoratives]]\n[[Category:Protective gear]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hat and stereotype for conspiracy theorists}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:30C3 TinFoil-Hat.jpg|alt=|thumb|Man in a tin foil hat at the [[Chaos Communication Congress]]]]\nA '''tin foil hat''' is a [[hat]] made from one or more sheets of [[aluminium foil]], or a piece of conventional headgear lined with foil, worn in the belief or hope that it shields the [[Human brain|brain]] from threats such as [[electromagnetic field]]s, [[mind control]], and [[telepathy|mind reading]]. The notion of wearing homemade headgear for such protection has become a popular [[stereotype]] and byword for [[paranoia]], [[persecutory delusions]], and belief in [[pseudoscience]] and [[conspiracy theories]].\n\n\"[[Tin foil]]\" is a common [[misnomer]] for [[aluminium foil]]; packaging metal foil was formerly made out of [[tin]] before it was replaced with [[aluminium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/foil-metallurgy|title=Foil - metallurgy|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Origin  ==\nAn early allusion to an \"insulative electrical contrivance encircling the head during thought\" appears in the unusual 1909 [[non-fiction]] publication ''Atomic Consciousness'' <ref name=\"Bathurst1909\">{{cite book |title=Atomic Consciousness Abridgement |first=James |last=Bathurst |publisher=W. Manning, London |year=1909}}</ref> by self-proclaimed \"seer\" John Palfrey (aka \"James Bathurst\") who believed such headgear was not effective for his \"retention of thoughts and ideas\" against a supposed \"telepathic impactive impingement\".<ref name=\"Wilson2016\">{{cite magazine |title=Atomic-Consciousness |magazine=[[Fortean Times]] |date=June 2016 |first=Daniel |last=Wilson}}</ref>\n\nSome people have a belief that such hats prevent [[mind control by governments]], spies, or paranormal beings that employ [[Extrasensory perception|ESP]] or the [[microwave auditory effect]]. People in many countries who believe they are \"[[Electronic harassment|targeted individuals]]\", subject to government spying or harassment, have developed websites, conference calls, and support meetings to discuss their concerns, including the idea of protective headgear.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/10/AR2007011001399_3.html|title=Mind Games|last=Weinberger|first=Sharon|date=14 January 2007|work=Washington Post|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> Over time the term \"tin foil hat\" has become associated with [[paranoia]] and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]].<ref name=\"Crazy\">{{cite web|title=Hey Crazy--Get a New Hat |url=http://www.bostonist.com/archives/2005/11/15/hey_crazyget_a_new_hat.php |accessdate=5 April 2007 |date=15 November 2005 |publisher=Bostonist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503051428/http://www.bostonist.com/archives/2005/11/15/hey_crazyget_a_new_hat.php |archivedate=3 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== Scientific basis ==\n[[Electromagnetic radiation and health|Effects of strong electromagnetic radiation on health]] have been documented for quite some time.<ref name=\"Ref_1979\">{{cite journal |title=Neurophysiologic effects of Radiofrequency and Microwave Radiation |journal=Bulletin of the New York Academy of Medicine |volume=55 |issue=11 |first=W. R. |last=Adey |date=December 1979 |pages=1079\u20131093|pmid=295243 }}</ref> The efficiency of a metal enclosure in blocking electromagnetic radiation depends on the thickness of the foil, as dictated by the \"[[skin effect|skin depth]]\" of the conductor for a particular wave frequency range of the radiation. For half-millimetre-thick aluminum foil, radiation above about 20&nbsp;kHz (i.e., including both [[AM band|AM]] and [[FM band]]s) would be partially blocked, although aluminum foil is not sold in this thickness, so numerous layers of foil would be required to achieve this effect.<ref name=\"Jackson1998\">{{cite book |title=Classical Electrodynamics |first=John David |last=Jackson |publisher=Wiley Press |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-471-30932-1 }}</ref>\n\nA belief also exists that aluminum foil is a protective measure against the effects of [[electromagnetic radiation]] (EMR) for many unspecified EMR frequencies.{{cn|date=July 2019}} There are some allegations that EMR exposure has negative health consequences.<ref name=\"Lean2006\">{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/environment/article362557.ece |title=Electronic smog |work=The Independent |date=7 May 2006 |accessdate=9 June 2009 |location=London |first=Geoffrey |last=Lean |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517030959/http://news.independent.co.uk/environment/article362557.ece |archivedate=17 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1962, [[Allan H. Frey]] discovered that the [[microwave auditory effect]] (i.e., the reception of the induced sounds by radio-frequency electromagnetic signals heard as clicks and buzzes) can be blocked by a patch of [[wire mesh]] (rather than foil) placed above the [[temporal lobe]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frey|first=Allan H.|date=1962-07-01|title=Human auditory system response to modulated electromagnetic energy|url=http://jap.physiology.org/content/17/4/689|journal=Journal of Applied Physiology|language=en|volume=17|issue=4|pages=689\u2013692|issn=8750-7587|pmid=13895081|doi=10.1152/jappl.1962.17.4.689}}</ref><ref name=\"Elder & Chou 2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/bem.10163 |last1=Elder |first1=Joe A. |last2=Chou |first2=C.K. |year=2003 |title=Auditory response to pulsed radiofrequency energy |journal=Bioelectromagnetics |volume=24 |issue=S6 |pages=S162\u201373 |issn=0197-8462 |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/106565261/abstract|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121104224846/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/106565261/abstract|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-04|pmid=14628312}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe usage of a metal foil hat for protection against interference of the mind was mentioned in a science fiction short story by [[Julian Huxley]], \"[[The Tissue-Culture King]]\", first published in 1926,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MkQPztA7TTIC&pg=PA118 p. 118]</ref><ref name=\"Huxley1926\">{{cite journal|last=Huxley|first=Julian|authorlink=Julian Huxley|title=The Tissue-Culture King: A Parable of Modern Science|volume= XV|year=1925\u20131926|journal=[[The Yale Review]]|pages=479\u2013504|url=http://yalereview.yale.edu/volume-xv-1925-1926}}</ref> in which the protagonist discovers that \"caps of metal foil\" can block the effects of [[telepathy]].<ref name=\"Huxley1927\">{{cite journal|last=Huxley|first=Julian|title=The Tissue-Culture King|date= August 1927|journal=[[Amazing Stories]]|quote=Well, we had discovered that metal was relatively impervious to the telepathic effect, and had prepared for ourselves a sort of tin pulpit, behind which we could stand while conducting experiments. This, combined with caps of metal foil, enormously reduced the effects on ourselves.}}</ref>\n\nTin foil hats have appeared in such films such as ''[[Signs (film)|Signs]]'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5682464/area-51-raid-hat/|title=Area 51 Raid But Make It Fashion: It Takes a Lot to Stand Out at Alien-Themed Festival But This Guy's Tin Foil Hat Is Working|last=Lang|first=Cady|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Futurama: Into the Wild Green Yonder]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/36153/futurama-into-the-wild-green-yonder/|title=Futurama: Into The Wild Green Yonder|last=Miller III|first=Randy|date=February 1, 2009|website=[[DVD Talk]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book series ''[[Artemis Fowl]]'' by [[Eoin Colfer]] features a paranoid [[centaur]] character named Foaly, who wears a tin-foil hat to protect from mind-readers. The novel ''[[Idiots in the Machine]]'' by [[Edward Savio]] portrays a character who believes tin foil keeps harmful gamma rays away, becoming a media sensation after marketing a successful line of foil hats to Chicago.\n\nThe 2019 [[HBO]] television series ''[[Watchmen (TV series)|Watchmen]]'' features the character Wade Tillman / Looking Glass, a police officer who wears a mask made of reflective foil, and while off-duty, a cap lined in foil to protect his mind from alien psychic attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/watchmen-show-easter-eggs-episode-5/|title=Watchmen: Biggest Comic Easter Eggs in Episode 5|last=Erdmann|first=Kevin|date=November 18, 2019|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nIn 2020, an [[Uzbekistan]]i citizen tried to cross the [[Belarus]]ian-[[Lithuania]]n border illegally using aluminum foil padding of the attire and a tin foil hat, to avoid detection by [[thermographic camera]]s. It was reported that the border guards face similar violations quite regularly.<ref>[https://newgrodno.by/society/shapka-nevidimka-iz-folgi-ne-pomogla-zhitelyu-uzbekistana-nezakonno-peresech-granitsu-on-zaderzhan-litovskimi-pogranichnikami/ \u00ab\u0428\u0430\u043f\u043a\u0430-\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0430\u00bb \u0438\u0437 \u0444\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044e \u0423\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043d\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0447\u044c \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0443. \u041e\u043d \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d \u043b\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Electromagnetic hypersensitivity]]\n* [[Electromagnetic radiation and health]]\n* [[Electronic harassment]]\n* [[Electrophonic hearing]]\n* [[Electrostatic discharge materials]]\n* [[Embassy attack accusations in Cuba]] (and China)\n* [[Faraday cage]]\n* [[The Hum]]\n* [[Microwave auditory effect]]\n* [[On the Origin of the \"Influencing Machine\" in Schizophrenia]]\n* [[Sonic weapon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|Tin foil hats}}\n\n{{Hats}}\n{{Pseudoscience|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tin Foil Hat}}\n[[Category:Hats]]\n[[Category:Mind control]]\n[[Category:Paranoia]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Pejoratives]]\n[[Category:Protective gear]]\n", "name_user": "Barkeep49", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Idiots in the Machineclosed as soft delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tin_foil_hat"}
{"title_page": "Trolls World Tour", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 animated film directed by Walt Dohrn}}\n{{Redirect|Trolls 2|the 1990 comedy horror film|Troll 2}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trolls World Tour\n| image          = Trolls_World_Tour_poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Walt Dohrn]]\n| producer       = [[Gina Shay]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel<br>Glenn Berger]]\n* Elizabeth Tippet\n* [[Maya Forbes]]\n* [[Wallace Wolodarsky]]\n}}\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Jonathan Aibel\n* Glenn Berger\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Troll doll]]s|[[Thomas Dam]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[Rachel Bloom]]\n* [[James Corden]]\n* [[Ron Funches]]\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n* [[Anderson Paak]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]]\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]]\n* [[Mary J. Blige]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Theodore Shapiro]]<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\">{{cite news |last1=Sarto |first1=Dan |title=DreamWorks Animation Reveals 21 Posters and Cast for \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 |url= https://dazntvstreams.com/movies/ |work=Animation World Network |date=20 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Nick Fletcher]]\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|04|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90\u2013100 million<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/as-a-virus-upends-hollywood-may-never-be-a-return-normal-1286691 | last1=Keegan | first1=Rebecca | title=As a Virus Upends Hollywood, There May Never Be a Return to Normal | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=December 26, 2019 | accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=VarietyTheaters>{{cite news |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Straight to Streaming \u2014 Sign of the Times or the New Normal? |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/trolls-world-tour-streaming-theatrical-window-future-1234573263/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $1.9 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1535018497/ | title=Trolls World Tour (2020) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Trolls World Tour''''' is a 2020 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[jukebox musical]] film produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film is a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', directed by [[Walt Dohrn]] with co-direction by David P. Smith, produced by [[Gina Shay]], and written by [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger]], Elizabeth Tippet, [[Maya Forbes]] and [[Wallace Wolodarsky]], from a story by Aibel and Berger. The film stars [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Ron Funches]], [[James Corden]], [[Kunal Nayyar]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Sam Rockwell]], [[Kenan Thompson]] and [[Rachel Bloom]].\n\n''Trolls World Tour'' was theatrically released in the United States on April 10, 2020. Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], the film was also released for [[video on demand|digital rental]] on the same day.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Plot|film|date=April 2020}}\nA celebration of the Techno Trolls is crashed by the [[Rock music|Rock Trolls]], led by evil Queen Barb. After Barb destroys his DJ station with her [[guitar]]'s power, King Trollex is forced to surrender the blue string that powers [[Techno]] music. \n\nPoppy, still adjusting to her new role as queen, receives a message from Barb that invites all Trolls to a party to unite their music. Her father reveals that there are different kinds of Trolls scattered through their land. The six primary tribes are each represented by a different style of music: [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Funk]]. [[Classical music|Classical]], [[Techno]], [[Country music|Country]], and [[Rock music|Rock]]. Each musical style being powered by a magical string kept by the leader of each tribe. Having separated their tribes following discord and disagreement over which style of music was the best, Poppy wants to help Barb unite the different forms of music, but both her father and Branch warn her not to trust Barb's intentions and to accept that the other Trolls are different. Poppy does not listen, and sends a cheerful reply to Barb via Debbie, Barb's pet bat.\n\nMeanwhile, Barb gloats over her victory of snatching the [[Techno]] string, revealing her plan to string an enchanted guitar with all six strings, and play a power chord strong enough to destroy all other music, replacing it with [[Rock music|rock]].\n\nWanting to prove herself as a good queen, Poppy travels via air balloon to recruit the other groups of Trolls, Branch joining her in an attempt to express his feelings towards her. Biggie accidentally stows aboard the balloon, and joins them. Meanwhile, Cooper, who feels like the black sheep among the Pop trolls, goes on a journey himself to find Trolls who look like him.\n\nThe balloon ends up in the land of [[Classical]] Trolls, which, to Poppy's horror, is in ruins. A single small [[flute]] named Pennywhistle tells Poppy their town had been decimated by Barb's armada, who captured all the citizens and stole the yellow Classical string. Poppy decides to now unite the other Trolls to stop Barb. Branch and Biggie both urge her to return home to protect the pink Pop string, but Poppy reveals it hidden in her hair. They then travel to the [[Country]] Trolls' land, but after introducing themselves with a loud medley of pop songs, are jailed by an offended Delta Dawn. A Country Troll named Hickory, who claims he is moved by Poppy's motives, breaks them out, leading to a chase to a ravine, where the group falls into a river. Branch does not trust Hickory, even when the Troll builds a raft to take the group downstream. The conversation is interrupted by Chaz, a [[Smooth Jazz]] Troll who was hired as a bounty hunter to catch Poppy for Barb, who was incredibly offended by Poppy's reply letter. Hickory incapacitates Chaz, but Biggie, disillusioned by Poppy's poor leadership, decides to return home. Shortly after, the group is abducted by a space ship wielding magical soap bubbles.\n\nInside the spaceship, the group meets the [[Funk]] Trolls, and meets up with Cooper, who is revealed to have been a long lost identical twin prince of Funk all along. Cooper tells Poppy he finds comfort in identifying with both [[Pop music|Pop]] and [[Funk]], and his parents, King Quincy and Queen Essence, reveal to Poppy that long ago the original [[Pop music|Pop]] Trolls had attempted to steal the strings and remix the other five music styles into Pop, forcing the other Trolls to each take one string and divide their tribes to save their music. Quincy explains to Poppy that differences are not bad, and trying to make all Trolls the same does not help the problem.\n\nAfter the Rock Trolls hijack the Funk Trolls' ship to steal the purple Funk String, Cooper ejects the group in bubbles, accidentally separating Hickory from the two. Branch and Poppy fight when Poppy refuses to return home to their friends, and Branch admonishes her insisting she cannot be a good queen if she is a poor listener, and the two go their separate ways, heartbroken. Branch is soon captured by both [[K-Pop]] and [[Reggaeton]] bounty hunters. However, he eventually convinces them to stop capturing and fighting and save Poppy and all music.\n\nPoppy reunites with Hickory, showing him the Pop string. Hickory urges her to return home, but suddenly is revealed to have been a [[Yodel]] Troll all along. He and another Yodel Troll, Dickory, had been hired to capture her for Barb, but Hickory had a change of heart. Before she can escape, Poppy is then captured personally by Barb, who takes possession of the sixth and final string. \n\nBiggie returns home and seeing it in shambles, feels remorse over abandoning Poppy. He gathers together their remaining friends to go rescue her and Branch, entering the land of the Rock Trolls.\n\nBarb has Poppy imprisoned over a large concert stage where all the captured Trolls are the audience, and admits she empathizes with Poppy's attempts to be a good queen, as she is trying to make rock supreme to prove her own leadership. Barb uses her enchanted guitar during the concert to turn Branch, and the leaders of the other lands into rock zombies. Poppy seemingly is transformed into a rock zombie when she falls onto the stage, but upon grabbing Barb's guitar, is revealed to have been wearing gumdrop earplugs. She admonishes Barb for being a poor queen by not taking time to listen to her people, and smashes the guitar. While it snaps the possessed trolls out of their rock zombie state, it destroys the strings, ending [[music]], and causing all the trolls to lose their colors, much to Barb\u2019s anguish.\n\nCooper hears his heartbeat over a microphone, and creates a rhythmic beat with it, other trolls joining in with clapping, stomping, and other forms of soundmaking, reviving the power of their music, and Poppy encourages everyone to [[sing]] together as their colors are restored. Realizing how important other forms of [[music]] are, and encouraged by her father Thrash, Barb joins in, regaining her colors, and eagerly accepts Poppy's offer of friendship. \n\nBranch is finally able to profess his love to Poppy who reciprocates his feelings, and everyone performs together, all Trolls finally reunited while celebrating their differences.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], Bridget and King Gristle arrive to the Pop Troll village, unaware of the events that have taken place, and worried they have missed the party.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]] as Queen Poppy, the optimistic Queen of the Pop Trolls and Branch's love interest.\n* [[Justin Timberlake]] as Branch, an over-cautious, good-hearted survivalist Pop Troll and Poppy's love interest.\n* [[Rachel Bloom]] as Queen Barb, the wild-hearted and evil Queen of the Hard Rock Trolls and Thrash's daughter.\n* [[James Corden]] as Biggie, a chubby, friendly pop Troll.\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] as King Thrash, former King of the Hard Rock Trolls, and Barb's semi-senile father.\n* [[Anderson Paak]] as Prince D, a Funk Troll who is Quincy and Essence's son and Cooper\u2019s twin brother.\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] as King Quincy, the King of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Mary J. Blige]] as Queen Essence, the Queen of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]] as Delta Dawn, the half-troll half-horse leader of the Country Trolls.\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as Hickory, a Yodel Troll who is disguised as a Country Troll.\n* [[Icona Pop]] as Satin and Chenille, two Pop Troll twins who are conjoined by the hair.\n* [[Ron Funches]] as Cooper, a Pop troll who walks on all fours and who is later revealed to be a Funk Troll.\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]] as Guy Diamond, a glittery silver Pop Troll with a highly auto-tuned voice.\n* [[Jamie Dornan]] as Chaz, a Smooth Jazz Troll whose music has hypnotic effects.\n* [[J Balvin]] as Tresillo, the leader of the Reggaeton Trolls.\n* [[Kenan Thompson]] as Tiny Diamond, a Hip-Hop Troll and Guy Diamond's newborn son.\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Mr. Dinkles, Biggie's pet worm.\n* [[Walt Dohrn]] as \n** Smidge, a small female pop Troll with a masculine voice.\n** Cloud Guy, an anthropomorphic cloud.\n** King Peppy, Poppy's father and the former King of the pop Trolls. He was previously voiced by [[Jeffrey Tambor]].\n** Fuzzbert, a hair pop troll with legs.\n** Additional voices\n* [[Ester Dean]] as Legsly, a Pop Troll who can make her legs really long at will.\n* [[Gustavo Dudamel]] as Trollzart, a troll with wings and the leader of the Classical Trolls.\n* [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] as King Trollex, the King of the Techno Trolls.\n* [[Flula Borg]] as Dickory, a Yodel Troll who is inside of the back of Hickory\n* [[Charlyne Yi]] as Pennywhistle, a whistle from the Classical Troll village.\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]] as Bridget\n* [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]] as King Gristle\n* [[Betsy Sodaro]] as Clampers Buttonwillow\n* [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|The McElroy Brothers]] as Skyscraper\n** [[Justin McElroy|Justin]] also voices Techno Beat Drop Button and Tumbleweed.\n** [[Travis McElroy|Travis]] also voices Rock Tear\n** [[Griffin McElroy|Griffin]] also voices Country Tear\n* [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]] as the K-Pop Gang:<ref name=BillboardTrolls2020>{{cite news|title=Red Velvet Share Troll-ish Character Posters for 'Trolls World Tour'|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/international/8550504/red-velvet-share-troll-ish-character-posters-for-trolls-world|work=Billboard|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Wendy (singer)|Wendy]] voices Wani, the leader of the K-Pop Trolls and Tresillo\u2019s rival. She also voices Poppy in the Korean dub.\n** [[Irene (singer)|Irene]] voices Baby Bun, Gomdori\u2019s best friend.\n** [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]] voices Gomdori, Wani\u2019s lieutenant.\n** [[Joy (singer)|Joy]] voices Ari, Wani\u2019s third in command.\n** [[Yeri (singer)|Yeri]] voices Kim-Petit, the most silent of the K-Pop Trolls.}}\n\n==Production==\nOn February 28, 2017, [[Universal Pictures]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]] announced a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', with [[Anna Kendrick]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] reprising their roles as Poppy and Branch.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Universal DreamWorks Animation Announces \u2018Trolls 2\u2019; Sets for April 10, 2020|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/trolls-2-announced-april-2020-dreamworks-animation-1201998983/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, podcasters the [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|McElroy brothers]] began campaigning for roles in the film via a podcast titled \"The McElroy Brothers Will Be in Trolls 2\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maximumfun.org/my-brother-my-brother-and-me/mcelroy-brothers-will-be-trolls-2-chapter-1|title=The McElroy Brothers Will Be In Trolls 2: Chapter 1 {{!}} Maximum Fun|website=www.maximumfun.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> Following the campaign's success, DreamWorks confirmed in September 2018 that the McElroy brothers would make cameo appearances in ''World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/09/trolls-world-tour-mcelroy-brothers-casting |title=The Unbelievable True Story of How Three Podcasters Trolled Their Way into Trolls 2 |last=Bradley |first=Laura |date=September 11, 2018 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Sam Rockwell]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Jamie Dornan]] and [[Flula Borg]] were added to the cast in May 2018. Corden, Icona Pop, Funches, and Nayyar returned to reprise their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chance-rapper-joins-cast-trolls-2-1110763|title=Chance the Rapper Joins the Cast of 'Trolls 2'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> On June 12, 2018, the film was retitled as ''Trolls World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/features/new-details-revealed-about-dreamworks-trolls-sequel/|title=New Details Revealed About DreamWorks\u2019 \u2018Trolls\u2019 Sequel|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/laverne-cox-disclosure-trans-lives-on-screen-documentary-1202843851/|title=Film News Roundup: Laverne Cox Boards 'Disclosure: Trans Lives on Screen' Documentary|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|first2=Dave|last2=McNary|date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, it was confirmed that [[Kelly Clarkson]] had joined the cast, and will perform an original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/kelly-clarkson-trolls-2-perform-original-song-1202476507/|title=Kelly Clarkson Joins \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 & Will Perform Original Song|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, along with promotional posters, new cast members have been announced, which include: [[J Balvin]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Rachel Bloom]], [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Ester Dean]] and [[Gustavo Dudamel]].<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\"/>\n\nAlong with Timberlake, Clarkson, Paak, Blige and Clinton, songs are provided by [[Chris Stapleton]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].\n\nThe first single from the movie's soundtrack, \"[[The Other Side (SZA and Justin Timberlake song)|The Other Side]]\", by Timberlake and SZA, was released on February 26, 2020. The ''[[Trolls World Tour (soundtrack)|Trolls World Tour: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' was released on March 13, 2020.\n\n==Music==\n# The Other Side by SZA & Justin Timberlake\n# One More Time\n# Rock You Like a Hurricane\n# Trolls Wanna Have a Good Time\n# Crazy Train\n# Symphony No. 5 in C Minor\n# Born to Die by Kelly Clarkson\n# Trolls 2 Many Hits Mashup by Anna Kendrick, Timberlake, James Corden, Icona Pop & the Pop Trolls\n# Leaving Lonesome Flats by Dierks Bentley\n# I Fall to Pieces by Sam Rockwell\n# Atomic Dog World Tour Remix\n# It's All Love (History of Funk)\n# Perfect for Me by Timberlake\n# Russian Roulette by [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]\n# Mi Gente by J. Balvin & Willy William\n# Barracuda \n# Just Sing (Trolls World Tour) by Kendrick, James Corden, Kelly Clarkson, George Clinton, Mary J. Blige, Anderson. Paak, Rachel Bloom, Kenan Thompson\n# Don't Slack\n\n==Release==\n[[Universal Pictures]] originally planned to release ''Trolls World Tour'' theatrically in the United States on April 10, 2020.<ref name=Trolls2DateChange>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/fast-furious-9-easter-weekend-2020-release-date-trolls-2-valentines-day-opening-2020-1202181866/|title='Fast & Furious 9' Drives To Easter Weekend 2020; 'Trolls 2' Moves To Spring 2020 \u2013 Update|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> It was later pushed up to February 14, 2020 before being moved to April 17, 2020. Following the delay of ''[[No Time to Die]]'', it was once again pushed up to the original April 10 release date.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/trolls-world-tour-opening-easter-no-time-to-die-coronavirus-release-date-change-1202874398/|title='Trolls World Tour' Fills Easter Void Left By \u2018No Time To Die\u2019|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2020-03-04|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> It was also set to be released on March 20 in the United Kingdom, but due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], its release date was pushed back to April 6.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelson |first1=Alex |title=How to watch Trolls World Tour on Sky TV and Amazon Prime in the UK |url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/film/trolls-world-tour-how-watch-sky-tv-amazon-prime-release-date-cast-price-what-about-2531969 |website=iNews |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Universal announced that the film would be released simultaneously in theaters and for rental on digital platforms on April 10 in the United States due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Universal to Release 'Trolls World Tour' for Digital Rental on Same Day as Theatrical Release |url=https://www.thewrap.com/universal-to-release-trolls-world-tour-for-digital-rental-on-same-day-as-theatrical-release/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nOn June 20, 2019, DreamWorks released 22 character posters for the film, along with promotional film stills.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> On June 21, the first trailer was released.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yP86-TR6IME</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released on November 15, 2019. A third trailer was released on March 6, 2020, featuring the new release date.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|4|12|df=US}}, ''Trolls World Tour'' has grossed $40,000 in the United States and Canada, and $1.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $1.9 million.<ref name=BOM/> \n\nIn the U.S., the film made $40,000 in its first two days of release from 10 [[drive-in theater]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/vod-box-office-trolls-world-tour-number-1-amazon-prime-1202224477/|title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Opens #1 at Amazon Prime, and the Weekend Box Office|website=IndieWire}}</ref> Following its debut digital streaming weekend, it was reported by [[FandangoNow]] that the film had set the record for most streams on a release weekend by the company. The film also finished number one for [[Amazon Prime Instant Video|Amazon Prime]], [[Comcast]], [[Apple TV]], [[Vudu]], [[YouTube]], and [[DirecTV Now]], with Universal reporting it was purchased 10-times more than ''[[Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom]]'', which had made $2-3 million on its first day.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/04/trolls-world-tour-record-digital-weekend-opening-day-1202906947/ |title= \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019: Universal Reports Record Digital Weekend; 10x Higher Than \u2018Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom\u2019 Opening Day|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' estimated that due to the film's approximate $90 million production cost, plus another $30 million spent on marketing (although rival studios claim Universal spent more than that), the film could [[break-even]] if 9\u201312 million people rent the film, resulting in about $200 million in revenue.<ref name=DeadlineProfit>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/04/trolls-world-tour-vod-box-office-movie-profits-universal-coronavirus-1202903913/ |title= Will \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Profit Off Universal\u2019s Experimental VOD (& Drive-In Theater) Model?|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 72% based on 96 reviews with an average rating of 6.14/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"A fun follow-up for fans of the original, ''Trolls World Tour'' offers a second helping of colorful animation, infectious energy, and sing-along songs.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Trolls World Tour (2020) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/trolls_world_tour |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 51 out of 100, based on 27 critic reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\" receiving 10 positive, 16 mixed, and 1 negative review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/trolls-world-tour|title=Trolls World Tour Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dreamworks.com/movies/trolls-world-tour}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt6587640}}\n\n{{Trolls}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Trolls (film)]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about trolls]]\n[[Category:Films based on toys]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Theodore Shapiro]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 animated film directed by Walt Dohrn}}\n{{Redirect|Trolls 2|the 1990 comedy horror film|Troll 2}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trolls World Tour\n| image          = Trolls_World_Tour_poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Walt Dohrn]]\n| producer       = [[Gina Shay]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel<br>Glenn Berger]]\n* Elizabeth Tippet\n* [[Maya Forbes]]\n* [[Wallace Wolodarsky]]\n}}\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Jonathan Aibel\n* Glenn Berger\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[Troll doll]]s|[[Thomas Dam]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[Rachel Bloom]]\n* [[James Corden]]\n* [[Ron Funches]]\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n* [[Anderson Paak]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]]\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]]\n* [[Mary J. Blige]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Theodore Shapiro]]<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\">{{cite news |last1=Sarto |first1=Dan |title=DreamWorks Animation Reveals 21 Posters and Cast for \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 |url= https://dazntvstreams.com/movies/ |work=Animation World Network |date=20 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Nick Fletcher]]\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|04|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 91 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90\u2013100 million<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/as-a-virus-upends-hollywood-may-never-be-a-return-normal-1286691 | last1=Keegan | first1=Rebecca | title=As a Virus Upends Hollywood, There May Never Be a Return to Normal | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=December 26, 2019 | accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=VarietyTheaters>{{cite news |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Straight to Streaming \u2014 Sign of the Times or the New Normal? |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/trolls-world-tour-streaming-theatrical-window-future-1234573263/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $1.9 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1535018497/ | title=Trolls World Tour (2020) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Trolls World Tour''''' is a 2020 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[jukebox musical]] film produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film is a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', directed by [[Walt Dohrn]] with co-direction by David P. Smith, produced by [[Gina Shay]], and written by [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger]], Elizabeth Tippet, [[Maya Forbes]] and [[Wallace Wolodarsky]], from a story by Aibel and Berger. The film stars [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Ron Funches]], [[James Corden]], [[Kunal Nayyar]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Sam Rockwell]], [[Kenan Thompson]] and [[Rachel Bloom]].\n\n''Trolls World Tour'' was theatrically released in the United States on April 10, 2020. Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], the film was also released for [[video on demand|digital rental]] on the same day.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Plot|film|date=April 2020}}\nA celebration of the Techno Trolls is crashed by the [[Rock music|Rock Trolls]], led by Queen Barb. After Barb destroys his DJ station with her [[guitar]]'s power, King Trollex is forced to surrender the blue string that powers [[Techno]] music. \n\nPoppy, still adjusting to her new role as queen, receives a message from Barb that invites all Trolls to a party to unite their music. Her father reveals that there are different kinds of Trolls scattered through their land. The six primary tribes are each represented by a different style of music: [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Funk]]. [[Classical music|Classical]], [[Techno]], [[Country music|Country]], and [[Rock music|Rock]]. Each musical style being powered by a magical string kept by the leader of each tribe. Having separated their tribes following discord and disagreement over which style of music was the best, Poppy wants to help Barb unite the different forms of music, but both her father and Branch warn her not to trust Barb's intentions and to accept that the other Trolls are different. Poppy does not listen, and sends a cheerful reply to Barb via Debbie, Barb's pet bat.\n\nMeanwhile, Barb gloats over her victory of snatching the [[Techno]] string, revealing her plan to string an enchanted guitar with all six strings, and play a power chord strong enough to destroy all other music, replacing it with [[Rock music|rock]].\n\nWanting to prove herself as a good queen, Poppy travels via air balloon to recruit the other groups of Trolls, Branch joining her in an attempt to express his feelings towards her. Biggie accidentally stows aboard the balloon, and joins them. Meanwhile, Cooper, who feels like the black sheep among the Pop trolls, goes on a journey himself to find Trolls who look like him.\n\nThe balloon ends up in the land of [[Classical]] Trolls, which, to Poppy's horror, is in ruins. A single small [[flute]] named Pennywhistle tells Poppy their town had been decimated by Barb's armada, who captured all the citizens and stole the yellow Classical string. Poppy decides to now unite the other Trolls to stop Barb. Branch and Biggie both urge her to return home to protect the pink Pop string, but Poppy reveals it hidden in her hair. They then travel to the [[Country]] Trolls' land, but after introducing themselves with a loud medley of pop songs, are jailed by an offended Delta Dawn. A Country Troll named Hickory, who claims he is moved by Poppy's motives, breaks them out, leading to a chase to a ravine, where the group falls into a river. Branch does not trust Hickory, even when the Troll builds a raft to take the group downstream. The conversation is interrupted by Chaz, a [[Smooth Jazz]] Troll who was hired as a bounty hunter to catch Poppy for Barb, who was incredibly offended by Poppy's reply letter. Hickory incapacitates Chaz, but Biggie, disillusioned by Poppy's poor leadership, decides to return home. Shortly after, the group is abducted by a space ship wielding magical soap bubbles.\n\nInside the spaceship, the group meets the [[Funk]] Trolls, and meets up with Cooper, who is revealed to have been a long lost identical twin prince of Funk all along. Cooper tells Poppy he finds comfort in identifying with both [[Pop music|Pop]] and [[Funk]], and his parents, King Quincy and Queen Essence, reveal to Poppy that long ago the original [[Pop music|Pop]] Trolls had attempted to steal the strings and remix the other five music styles into Pop, forcing the other Trolls to each take one string and divide their tribes to save their music. Quincy explains to Poppy that differences are not bad, and trying to make all Trolls the same does not help the problem.\n\nAfter the Rock Trolls hijack the Funk Trolls' ship to steal the purple Funk String, Cooper ejects the group in bubbles, accidentally separating Hickory from the two. Branch and Poppy fight when Poppy refuses to return home to their friends, and Branch admonishes her insisting she cannot be a good queen if she is a poor listener, and the two go their separate ways, heartbroken. Branch is soon captured by both [[K-Pop]] and [[Reggaeton]] bounty hunters. However, he eventually convinces them to stop capturing and fighting and save Poppy and all music.\n\nPoppy reunites with Hickory, showing him the Pop string. Hickory urges her to return home, but suddenly is revealed to have been a [[Yodel]] Troll all along. He and another Yodel Troll, Dickory, had been hired to capture her for Barb, but Hickory had a change of heart. Before she can escape, Poppy is then captured personally by Barb, who takes possession of the sixth and final string. \n\nBiggie returns home and seeing it in shambles, feels remorse over abandoning Poppy. He gathers together their remaining friends to go rescue her and Branch, entering the land of the Rock Trolls.\n\nBarb has Poppy imprisoned over a large concert stage where all the captured Trolls are the audience, and admits she empathizes with Poppy's attempts to be a good queen, as she is trying to make rock supreme to prove her own leadership. Barb uses her enchanted guitar during the concert to turn Branch, and the leaders of the other lands into rock zombies. Poppy seemingly is transformed into a rock zombie when she falls onto the stage, but upon grabbing Barb's guitar, is revealed to have been wearing gumdrop earplugs. She admonishes Barb for being a poor queen by not taking time to listen to her people, and smashes the guitar. While it snaps the possessed trolls out of their rock zombie state, it destroys the strings, ending [[music]], and causing all the trolls to lose their colors, much to Barb\u2019s anguish.\n\nCooper hears his heartbeat over a microphone, and creates a rhythmic beat with it, other trolls joining in with clapping, stomping, and other forms of soundmaking, reviving the power of their music, and Poppy encourages everyone to [[sing]] together as their colors are restored. Realizing how important other forms of [[music]] are, and encouraged by her father Thrash, Barb joins in, regaining her colors, and eagerly accepts Poppy's offer of friendship. \n\nBranch is finally able to profess his love to Poppy who reciprocates his feelings, and everyone performs together, all Trolls finally reunited while celebrating their differences.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], Bridget and King Gristle arrive to the Pop Troll village, unaware of the events that have taken place, and worried they have missed the party.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Anna Kendrick]] as Queen Poppy, the optimistic Queen of the Pop Trolls and Branch's love interest.\n* [[Justin Timberlake]] as Branch, an over-cautious, good-hearted survivalist Pop Troll and Poppy's love interest.\n* [[James Corden]] as Biggie, a chubby, friendly pop Troll.\n* [[Rachel Bloom]] as Queen Barb, the wild-hearted Queen of the Hard Rock Trolls and Thrash's daughter.\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] as King Thrash, former King of the Hard Rock Trolls, and Barb's semi-senile father.\n* [[Anderson Paak]] as Prince D, a Funk Troll who is Quincy and Essence's son and Cooper\u2019s twin brother.\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] as King Quincy, the King of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Mary J. Blige]] as Queen Essence, the Queen of the Funk Trolls.\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]] as Delta Dawn, the half-troll half-horse leader of the Country Trolls.\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as Hickory, a Yodel Troll who is disguised as a Country Troll.\n* [[Icona Pop]] as Satin and Chenille, two Pop Troll twins who are conjoined by the hair.\n* [[Ron Funches]] as Cooper, a Pop troll who walks on all fours and who is later revealed to be a Funk Troll.\n* [[Kunal Nayyar]] as Guy Diamond, a glittery silver Pop Troll with a highly auto-tuned voice.\n* [[Jamie Dornan]] as Chaz, a Smooth Jazz Troll whose music has hypnotic effects.\n* [[J Balvin]] as Tresillo, the leader of the Reggaeton Trolls.\n* [[Kenan Thompson]] as Tiny Diamond, a Hip-Hop Troll and Guy Diamond's newborn son.\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Mr. Dinkles, Biggie's pet worm.\n* [[Walt Dohrn]] as \n** Smidge, a small female pop Troll with a masculine voice.\n** Cloud Guy, an anthropomorphic cloud.\n** King Peppy, Poppy's father and the former King of the pop Trolls. He was previously voiced by [[Jeffrey Tambor]].\n** Fuzzbert, a hair pop troll with legs.\n** Additional voices\n* [[Ester Dean]] as Legsly, a Pop Troll who can make her legs really long at will.\n* [[Gustavo Dudamel]] as Trollzart, a troll with wings and the leader of the Classical Trolls.\n* [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] as King Trollex, the King of the Techno Trolls.\n* [[Flula Borg]] as Dickory, a Yodel Troll who is inside of the back of Hickory\n* [[Charlyne Yi]] as Pennywhistle, a whistle from the Classical Troll village.\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]] as Bridget\n* [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]] as King Gristle\n* [[Betsy Sodaro]] as Clampers Buttonwillow\n* [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|The McElroy Brothers]] as Skyscraper\n** [[Justin McElroy|Justin]] also voices Techno Beat Drop Button and Tumbleweed.\n** [[Travis McElroy|Travis]] also voices Rock Tear\n** [[Griffin McElroy|Griffin]] also voices Country Tear\n* [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]] as the K-Pop Gang:<ref name=BillboardTrolls2020>{{cite news|title=Red Velvet Share Troll-ish Character Posters for 'Trolls World Tour'|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/international/8550504/red-velvet-share-troll-ish-character-posters-for-trolls-world|work=Billboard|date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Wendy (singer)|Wendy]] voices Wani, the leader of the K-Pop Trolls and Tresillo\u2019s rival. She also voices Poppy in the Korean dub.\n** [[Irene (singer)|Irene]] voices Baby Bun, Gomdori\u2019s best friend.\n** [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]] voices Gomdori, Wani\u2019s lieutenant.\n** [[Joy (singer)|Joy]] voices Ari, Wani\u2019s third in command.\n** [[Yeri (singer)|Yeri]] voices Kim-Petit, the most silent of the K-Pop Trolls.}}\n\n==Production==\nOn February 28, 2017, [[Universal Pictures]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]] announced a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[Trolls (film)|Trolls]]'', with [[Anna Kendrick]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] reprising their roles as Poppy and Branch.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Universal DreamWorks Animation Announces \u2018Trolls 2\u2019; Sets for April 10, 2020|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/trolls-2-announced-april-2020-dreamworks-animation-1201998983/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, podcasters the [[My Brother, My Brother and Me|McElroy brothers]] began campaigning for roles in the film via a podcast titled \"The McElroy Brothers Will Be in Trolls 2\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maximumfun.org/my-brother-my-brother-and-me/mcelroy-brothers-will-be-trolls-2-chapter-1|title=The McElroy Brothers Will Be In Trolls 2: Chapter 1 {{!}} Maximum Fun|website=www.maximumfun.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> Following the campaign's success, DreamWorks confirmed in September 2018 that the McElroy brothers would make cameo appearances in ''World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/09/trolls-world-tour-mcelroy-brothers-casting |title=The Unbelievable True Story of How Three Podcasters Trolled Their Way into Trolls 2 |last=Bradley |first=Laura |date=September 11, 2018 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Sam Rockwell]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]], [[Jamie Dornan]] and [[Flula Borg]] were added to the cast in May 2018. Corden, Icona Pop, Funches, and Nayyar returned to reprise their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chance-rapper-joins-cast-trolls-2-1110763|title=Chance the Rapper Joins the Cast of 'Trolls 2'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> On June 12, 2018, the film was retitled as ''Trolls World Tour''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/features/new-details-revealed-about-dreamworks-trolls-sequel/|title=New Details Revealed About DreamWorks\u2019 \u2018Trolls\u2019 Sequel|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/laverne-cox-disclosure-trans-lives-on-screen-documentary-1202843851/|title=Film News Roundup: Laverne Cox Boards 'Disclosure: Trans Lives on Screen' Documentary|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|first2=Dave|last2=McNary|date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, it was confirmed that [[Kelly Clarkson]] had joined the cast, and will perform an original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/kelly-clarkson-trolls-2-perform-original-song-1202476507/|title=Kelly Clarkson Joins \u2018Trolls 2\u2019 & Will Perform Original Song|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, along with promotional posters, new cast members have been announced, which include: [[J Balvin]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Rachel Bloom]], [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Ester Dean]] and [[Gustavo Dudamel]].<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\"/>\n\nAlong with Timberlake, Clarkson, Paak, Blige and Clinton, songs are provided by [[Chris Stapleton]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].\n\nThe first single from the movie's soundtrack, \"[[The Other Side (SZA and Justin Timberlake song)|The Other Side]]\", by Timberlake and SZA, was released on February 26, 2020. The ''[[Trolls World Tour (soundtrack)|Trolls World Tour: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' was released on March 13, 2020.\n\n==Music==\n# The Other Side by SZA & Justin Timberlake\n# One More Time\n# Rock You Like a Hurricane\n# Trolls Wanna Have a Good Time\n# Crazy Train\n# Symphony No. 5 in C Minor\n# Born to Die by Kelly Clarkson\n# Trolls 2 Many Hits Mashup by Anna Kendrick, Timberlake, James Corden, Icona Pop & the Pop Trolls\n# Leaving Lonesome Flats by Dierks Bentley\n# I Fall to Pieces by Sam Rockwell\n# Atomic Dog World Tour Remix\n# It's All Love (History of Funk)\n# Perfect for Me by Timberlake\n# Russian Roulette by [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]\n# Mi Gente by J. Balvin & Willy William\n# Barracuda \n# Just Sing (Trolls World Tour) by Kendrick, James Corden, Kelly Clarkson, George Clinton, Mary J. Blige, Anderson. Paak, Rachel Bloom, Kenan Thompson\n# Don't Slack\n\n==Release==\n[[Universal Pictures]] originally planned to release ''Trolls World Tour'' theatrically in the United States on April 10, 2020.<ref name=Trolls2DateChange>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/fast-furious-9-easter-weekend-2020-release-date-trolls-2-valentines-day-opening-2020-1202181866/|title='Fast & Furious 9' Drives To Easter Weekend 2020; 'Trolls 2' Moves To Spring 2020 \u2013 Update|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> It was later pushed up to February 14, 2020 before being moved to April 17, 2020. Following the delay of ''[[No Time to Die]]'', it was once again pushed up to the original April 10 release date.<ref name=VarietyTrolls2020 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/trolls-world-tour-opening-easter-no-time-to-die-coronavirus-release-date-change-1202874398/|title='Trolls World Tour' Fills Easter Void Left By \u2018No Time To Die\u2019|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2020-03-04|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> It was also set to be released on March 20 in the United Kingdom, but due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], its release date was pushed back to April 6.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelson |first1=Alex |title=How to watch Trolls World Tour on Sky TV and Amazon Prime in the UK |url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/film/trolls-world-tour-how-watch-sky-tv-amazon-prime-release-date-cast-price-what-about-2531969 |website=iNews |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Universal announced that the film would be released simultaneously in theaters and for rental on digital platforms on April 10 in the United States due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Universal to Release 'Trolls World Tour' for Digital Rental on Same Day as Theatrical Release |url=https://www.thewrap.com/universal-to-release-trolls-world-tour-for-digital-rental-on-same-day-as-theatrical-release/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nOn June 20, 2019, DreamWorks released 22 character posters for the film, along with promotional film stills.<ref name=\"Trolls2PostersCast\" /> On June 21, the first trailer was released.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yP86-TR6IME</ref>\n\nA second trailer was released on November 15, 2019. A third trailer was released on March 6, 2020, featuring the new release date.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|4|12|df=US}}, ''Trolls World Tour'' has grossed $40,000 in the United States and Canada, and $1.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $1.9 million.<ref name=BOM/> \n\nIn the U.S., the film made $40,000 in its first two days of release from 10 [[drive-in theater]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/vod-box-office-trolls-world-tour-number-1-amazon-prime-1202224477/|title=\u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Opens #1 at Amazon Prime, and the Weekend Box Office|website=IndieWire}}</ref> Following its debut digital streaming weekend, it was reported by [[FandangoNow]] that the film had set the record for most streams on a release weekend by the company. The film also finished number one for [[Amazon Prime Instant Video|Amazon Prime]], [[Comcast]], [[Apple TV]], [[Vudu]], [[YouTube]], and [[DirecTV Now]], with Universal reporting it was purchased 10-times more than ''[[Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom]]'', which had made $2-3 million on its first day.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/04/trolls-world-tour-record-digital-weekend-opening-day-1202906947/ |title= \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019: Universal Reports Record Digital Weekend; 10x Higher Than \u2018Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom\u2019 Opening Day|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' estimated that due to the film's approximate $90 million production cost, plus another $30 million spent on marketing (although rival studios claim Universal spent more than that), the film could [[break-even]] if 9\u201312 million people rent the film, resulting in about $200 million in revenue.<ref name=DeadlineProfit>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/04/trolls-world-tour-vod-box-office-movie-profits-universal-coronavirus-1202903913/ |title= Will \u2018Trolls World Tour\u2019 Profit Off Universal\u2019s Experimental VOD (& Drive-In Theater) Model?|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 72% based on 96 reviews with an average rating of 6.14/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"A fun follow-up for fans of the original, ''Trolls World Tour'' offers a second helping of colorful animation, infectious energy, and sing-along songs.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Trolls World Tour (2020) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/trolls_world_tour |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 51 out of 100, based on 27 critic reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\" receiving 10 positive, 16 mixed, and 1 negative review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/trolls-world-tour|title=Trolls World Tour Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.dreamworks.com/movies/trolls-world-tour}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt6587640}}\n\n{{Trolls}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:Trolls (film)]]\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:2020s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about trolls]]\n[[Category:Films based on toys]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Theodore Shapiro]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:2020s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "name_user": "31.159.63.138", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCast)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trolls_World_Tour"}
{"title_page": "Michael Tidser", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Tidser\n| image = Tidser, Michael.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| fullname = Michael Tidser<ref>{{Hugman|26389|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|1|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = 1.82m<ref>{{Soccerway|michael-tidser/90929}}</ref>\n| currentclub = [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]]\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132009\n| youthclubs1 = [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Celtic]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs1 = [[\u00d6stersunds FK|\u00d6stersunds]]\n| caps1 = ?\n| goals1 = ?\n| years2 = 2010\u20132013\n| clubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n| caps2 = 103\n| goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs3 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]\n| caps3 = 11\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2014\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 16\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs6 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n| caps6 = 52\n| goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs7 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n| caps7 = 9\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs8 = [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]]\n| caps8 = \n| goals8 = \n| nationalyears1 = 2007\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-18 football team|Scotland U18]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 3\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update = 19:30, 4 February 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Michael Tidser''' (born 15 January 1990) is a Scottish [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KeltyHeartsFC/status/1224773698386833408|title=NEW SIGNING {{!}} We are delighted to welcome midfielder Michael Tidser to New Central Park.|last=Club|first=Kelty Hearts Football|date=2020-02-04|website=@KeltyHeartsFC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nTidser began his career with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], before spending a short spell in [[Sweden]] with [[\u00d6stersunds FK]]. Tidser then returned to Scotland to spend three seasons at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], where he made well over 100 appearances. Tidser then moved to English club [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]. After spells on loan with [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] and [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]], Tidser returned to Morton in 2015. After leaving Morton in 2019 he had a short spell with [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].\n\nHe is a former [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]] international and features in the 2012\u201313 First Division team of the year as Morton finished second in the league.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]], Tidser started his career with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and was [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the Under 19's before being released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/more-scottish-football/having-fallen-foul-of-a-cull-at-celtic-morton-s-carlo-monti-and-michael-tidser-aren-t-looking-back-in-anger-1.999168|title=Having fallen foul of a cull at Celtic, Morton's Carlo Monti and Michael Tidser aren't looking back in anger|publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|first=Stewart|last=Fisher|date=17 January 2010|accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> He then signed a short-term contract with [[Sweden|Swedish]] side [[\u00d6stersunds FK]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Makel appointed Ostersund coach|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/east_fife/8119858.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 June 2009|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Morton===\nAfter his contract expired with \u00d6stersunds, he signed an 18-month deal with [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/News/&action=fullnews&id=305|publisher=gmfc.net|title=New signing confirmed|date=13 January 2009|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116131539/http://www.gmfc.net/News/%26action%3Dfullnews%26id%3D305|archivedate=16 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTidser would make an impressive start for the club, which resulted winning Young Player of the Month for March 2010<ref name=\"award\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news.cfm?curpageid=945&newsid=3372|title=IRN-BRU Phenomenal Awards for March announced|publisher=Scottish Football League|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414002751/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news.cfm?curpageid=945|archivedate=14 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has been watched by [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] coach [[Kenny McDowall]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8631522.stm|title=Tuesday's Scottish gossip|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=20 April 2010|accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010/11 season, Tidser scored his first goal for the club, in a 2\u20130 win over [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Morton 2\u20130 Partick Thistle|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/8930152.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 August 2010|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> His impressive performance continued with [[Scottish Premier League]]'s [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] and League One side [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], but no avail.<ref>{{cite news|title=Friday's Scottish gossip|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/9275799.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Then, on 12 February 2011, Tidser then sent off after a second bookable offence, in a 1\u20130 loss against [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Falkirk 1\u20130 Morton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/9393237.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 February 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> After the match, Manager [[Allan Moore]] said he was disappointed with Tidser's action.<ref>{{cite news|title=Moore: Tids only has self to blame|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2011/02/15/410241-moore-tids-only-has-self-to-blame/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In April 2011, Tidser signed a new three-year deal with Morton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/04/15/412368-tidser-agrees-3year-ton-deal/|title=Tidser Agrees 3-year Ton Deal|publisher=[[Greenock Telegraph]]|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=15 April 2011|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011/12 season, Tidser started the season well, scoring his first goal of the season, before providing an assist for [[Peter MacDonald (footballer)|Peter MacDonald]] to score a winning goal, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] on 13 August 2011. A week later, on 23 August 2011, he scored again and setting up a goal for MacDonald, in the second round of the Scottish League Cup, in a 4\u20133 loss against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]. However, his early season was overshadowed with a knee problem.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser doubtful for Bairns clash|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/09/22/417645-tidser-doubtful-for-bairns-clash/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nervous wait on injuries|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/09/28/417785-nervous-wait-on-injuries/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=28 September 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Following an operation, it was  announced that he will be out for two-months, he was expected to come back in December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Darren: I can fill gap left by Tids|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/10/15/418516-darren-i-can-fill-gap-left-by-tids/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=15 October 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Soon in mid-November, Tidser resumed training.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fouad's foot break agony|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/11/16/419758--fouads-foot-break-agony/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=16 November 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Upon recovering from injury, Tidser spoke to the Greenock Telegraph describing his sidelined from injury as \"torture\" and hard to make a return.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser looking for return to action|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/12/10/420958-tidser-looking-for-return-to-action/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=10 December 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In January 2012, after [[Stuart McCaffrey]] was ruled out for the season, Tidser was made Morton's team captain just after his 22nd birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2012/01/20/422540-tidser-named-new-morton-captain/|title=Tidser named new Morton captain|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=20 January 2012|accessdate=20 January 2012|first=Chris|last=Tait}}</ref> On 20 March 2012, he scored his second goal of the season, in a 2\u20130 win over Falkirk.\n\nIn 2012\u201313 season, Tidser had a good season with the club, having made a good display to compete with Partick Thistle to get promoted to Scottish Premier League, which Morton finished second. On 6 October 2012 Tidser provided a double assist for [[Kevin Rutkiewicz]] and [[Mark McLaughlin]], in a 3\u20131 win over Partick. It wasn't until 29 December 2012 when Tidser scored twice, in a 4\u20132 win over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]. That was followed up on 26 January 2013 when he scored in a 1\u20130 win over [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]. His next goal came on 23 February 2013 when he, again, scored against Dunfermline Athletic, with the same result on 29 December 2012. On 16 March 2013, Tidser scored his final goal of the season, in a 3\u20130 win over [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]. During the season, he also made a good display by making assists. He also scored five times in the Scottish Cup, including a brace against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] and [[Turriff United F.C.|Turriff United]], which was scored in the Scottish Cup replay. However, Tidser suffered an groin injury, that ruled him out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Missing training is a pain for Tidser|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/04/27/455259-missing-training-is-a-pain-for-tidser/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=27 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter a great season, Tidser was nominated for the [[2012\u201313 Scottish First Division|2012\u201313 First Division]] Player of the Year.<ref name=\"tids\"/> It got better for Tidser when he won the supporters' club awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terrace Talk: Fans' view|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/news/freecontent/articles/2013/04/30/455456-terrace-talk-fans-view/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, Tidser was the subject of a \u00a350k bid from [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]], which was rejected by Morton chairman [[Douglas Rae (businessman)|Douglas Rae]] at first.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/06/21/461753-50k-bid-for-tidser-rejected/|title=\u00a350k bid for Tidser rejected|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=21 June 2013|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref> Soon the bid was made again, but this time it was accepted five days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser set for Rotherham talks|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/06/26/462192-exclusive-tidser-set-for-rotherham-talks/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=26 June 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n===Rotherham United===\nTidser officially signed for [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 3 July 2013.<ref name=\"tidser\">{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/07/03/463034-breaking-news-tidser-signs-for-rotherham/|title=BREAKING NEWS: Tidser signs for Rotherham|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> The following week, on 9 July 2013, Tidser played against his former club Morton; when brought on, as a late substitute, he was given a standing ovation by Morton's fans.<ref>{{cite news|title=Greenock Morton 0\u20130 Rotherham United FT|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/greenock-morton-0-0-rotherham-united-ft-1-5838529|publisher=Sheffield Telegraph|date=9 July 2013|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter featuring on the bench in the first two matches of the opening game of the [[2013\u201314 Rotherham United F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Tidser finally made his debut after coming on as a late substitute in a 2\u20131 win over [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]]. However his start at Rotherham United didn't go as planned for him as his appearances had \"mostly have been off the bench\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Double boost for County|url=http://sport.bt.com/sportfootball/football/scottishfootball/scottishpremierleaguepreviews/double-boost-for-county-S11363864071883|publisher=BT Sports|date=3 January 2014|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2014, Tidser joined [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] on loan until the end of the 2013\u201314 season, in order to help the club retain their [[Scottish Premiership]] status next season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Triple Signing |url=http://www.rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk/news/triple-signing.aspx |publisher=rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103211619/http://www.rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk/news/triple-signing.aspx |archivedate=3 January 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser backs Ross County to win survival battle|url=http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Ross-County/Tidser-backs-Ross-County-to-win-survival-battle-09042014.htm|publisher=The Highland News|date=9 April 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser made his Ross County debut the next day, coming on as a substitute in the second half, in a 1\u20130 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross County 2\u20130 St Johnstone|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25532745|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 January 2014|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser's playing time increased, playing in midfielder position and assisted twice in two games against [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] on 15 February 2014 and [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 22 February 2014. However, his knee injury put Tidser out for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish Premiership briefing |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/article/26854/9291061/scottish-premiership-briefing |publisher=Sporting Life |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330130528/http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/article/26854/9291061/scottish-premiership-briefing |archivedate=30 March 2015 }}</ref> Tidser made 16 appearances for Ross County and returned to his parent club at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Summer shake-up on cards at Ross County|url=http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Ross-County/Summer-shake-up-on-cards-at-Ross-County-14052014.htm|publisher=Highland News|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter making his return to Rotherham United, Tidser made his first appearance in a year for the club, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] in [[2014\u201315 Football League Cup#First round|the first round of the League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham United 1\u20130 (aet) Fleetwood Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28652512|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser made two more appearance for the club, against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in the league<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham United 0 \u2013 2 Watford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28749920|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> and another League Cup appearance against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea City 1\u20130 Rotherham United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28847204|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> But on 1 September 2014, in the last hour of Deadline Day, Tidser signed for [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on loan until January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Latics Land Player on Deadline Day |url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20140901-michael-tidser-signs-1892201.aspx |publisher=Oldham Athletic A.F.C. |accessdate=1 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330131657/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20140901-michael-tidser-signs-1892201.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> Tidser made his Oldham Athletic debut in [[2014\u201315 Football League Trophy#Northern section 2|the second round of Football League Trophy]], which they beat [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] 4\u20132 on penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oldham Athletic 2\u20132 (aet) (4\u20132 penalty shoot-out) Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29421215|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 February 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> However, Tidser struggled for the first team at the club and made seven appearance in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/loans-return-to-parent-clubs-2183169.aspx |title=Loans Return To Parent Clubs |publisher=Oldham Athletic A.F.C. |accessdate=30 March 2015 |date=6 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330134028/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/loans-return-to-parent-clubs-2183169.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\nHe was released in January 2015 after two years at Rotherham United, and was quickly on the radar of former club Morton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/01/13/521106-exclusive-morton-in-bid-for-tidser/|title=Morton in bid for Tidser|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themillers.co.uk/news/article/millers-agree-tidser-release-2192068.aspx |title=Millers agree Tidser release |publisher=Rotherham United F.C. |accessdate=30 March 2015 |date=9 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330131341/http://www.themillers.co.uk/news/article/millers-agree-tidser-release-2192068.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n===Return to Morton===\n\nIn January 2015, Tidser returned to Morton on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/01/22/522196-breaking-tidser-seals-morton-return/|title=Tidser seals Morton return|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=22 January 2015|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> He was unable, however, to play until the 2015\u201316 season due to [[FIFA]] transfer regulations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/greenock/articles/2015/01/23/522431-breaking-tidser-transfer-hits-red-tape/|title=Tidser transfer hits red tape|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=-Mitchell|date=23 January 2015|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> Because of this, Tidser played in the club's reserve matches, in order to maintain his fitness throughout the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser stays sharp in Morton Under-20s|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/03/20/528062-tidser-stays-sharp-in-morton-under20s/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis 2015\u201316 season with Morton was limited to very few appearances before finally being ruled out all together in March after suffering a suspected [[hernia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/14342008.Injured_Morton_star_s_season_could_be_over/|title=Injured Morton star's season could be over|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=15 March 2016|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Tidser signed a two-year extension with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/2017/06/08/tidser-signs-two-year-contract-extension/|title=Tidser signs two-year contract|publisher=Greenock Morton F.C.|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=8 June 2017|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nTidser made three appearances for both the Scotland [[Scotland national under-18 football team|under-18]] and [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] sides, scoring once for the under-18's against [[Turkey national under-18 football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=2492&playerID=39949&squadID=9|title=Michael Tidser|publisher=Scottish Football Association|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 4 November 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colsp