/456050-moore-players-should-put-uncertainty-behind-them/#|title=Moore: Players should put uncertainty behind them|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=3 May 2013|accessdate=3 May 2013|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{2012\u201313 PFA Scotland First Division Team of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tidser, Michael}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Oldham Athletic A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:\u00d6stersunds FK players]]\n[[Category:Ross County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People from Dennistoun]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Michael Tidser\n| image = Tidser, Michael.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| fullname = Michael Tidser<ref>{{Hugman|26389|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|1|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = 1.82m<ref>{{Soccerway|michael-tidser/90929}}</ref>\n| currentclub = [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]]\n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132009 | youthclubs1 = [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Celtic]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs1 = [[\u00d6stersunds FK|\u00d6stersunds]]       | caps1 = ?   | goals1 = ?\n| years2 = 2010\u20132013 | clubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]            | caps2 = 103 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs3 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]          | caps3 = 11  | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2014      | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] (loan)           | caps4 = 16  | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] (loan) | caps5 = 5   | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2015\u20132019 | clubs6= [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]             | caps6 = 102 | goals6 = 9\n| years7 = 2019\u20132020 | clubs7= [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]                             | caps7 = 9   | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2020\u2013     | clubs8= [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]]                   | caps8 =    | goals8 = \n| nationalyears1 = 2007 | nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-18 football team|Scotland U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008 | nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update = 19:30, 4 February 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Michael Tidser''' (born 15 January 1990) is a Scottish [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Kelty Hearts F.C.|Kelty Hearts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KeltyHeartsFC/status/1224773698386833408|title=NEW SIGNING {{!}} We are delighted to welcome midfielder Michael Tidser to New Central Park.|last=Club|first=Kelty Hearts Football|date=2020-02-04|website=@KeltyHeartsFC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nTidser began his career with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], before spending a short spell in [[Sweden]] with [[\u00d6stersunds FK]]. Tidser then returned to Scotland to spend three seasons at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], where he made well over 100 appearances. Tidser then moved to English club [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]. After spells on loan with [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] and [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]], Tidser returned to Morton in 2015. After leaving Morton in 2019 he had a short spell with [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].\n\nHe is a former [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]] international and features in the 2012\u201313 First Division team of the year as Morton finished second in the league.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]], Tidser started his career with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and was [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the Under 19's before being released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/more-scottish-football/having-fallen-foul-of-a-cull-at-celtic-morton-s-carlo-monti-and-michael-tidser-aren-t-looking-back-in-anger-1.999168|title=Having fallen foul of a cull at Celtic, Morton's Carlo Monti and Michael Tidser aren't looking back in anger|publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|first=Stewart|last=Fisher|date=17 January 2010|accessdate=13 February 2011}}</ref> He then signed a short-term contract with [[Sweden|Swedish]] side [[\u00d6stersunds FK]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Makel appointed Ostersund coach|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/east_fife/8119858.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 June 2009|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Morton===\nAfter his contract expired with \u00d6stersunds, he signed an 18-month deal with [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/News/&action=fullnews&id=305|publisher=gmfc.net|title=New signing confirmed|date=13 January 2009|accessdate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116131539/http://www.gmfc.net/News/%26action%3Dfullnews%26id%3D305|archivedate=16 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTidser would make an impressive start for the club, which resulted winning Young Player of the Month for March 2010<ref name=\"award\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news.cfm?curpageid=945&newsid=3372|title=IRN-BRU Phenomenal Awards for March announced|publisher=Scottish Football League|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=13 April 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414002751/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news.cfm?curpageid=945|archivedate=14 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has been watched by [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] coach [[Kenny McDowall]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8631522.stm|title=Tuesday's Scottish gossip|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=20 April 2010|accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010/11 season, Tidser scored his first goal for the club, in a 2\u20130 win over [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Morton 2\u20130 Partick Thistle|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/8930152.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 August 2010|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> His impressive performance continued with [[Scottish Premier League]]'s [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] and League One side [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], but no avail.<ref>{{cite news|title=Friday's Scottish gossip|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/9275799.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Then, on 12 February 2011, Tidser then sent off after a second bookable offence, in a 1\u20130 loss against [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Falkirk 1\u20130 Morton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/9393237.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 February 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> After the match, Manager [[Allan Moore]] said he was disappointed with Tidser's action.<ref>{{cite news|title=Moore: Tids only has self to blame|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2011/02/15/410241-moore-tids-only-has-self-to-blame/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=15 February 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In April 2011, Tidser signed a new three-year deal with Morton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/04/15/412368-tidser-agrees-3year-ton-deal/|title=Tidser Agrees 3-year Ton Deal|publisher=[[Greenock Telegraph]]|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=15 April 2011|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011/12 season, Tidser started the season well, scoring his first goal of the season, before providing an assist for [[Peter MacDonald (footballer)|Peter MacDonald]] to score a winning goal, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] on 13 August 2011. A week later, on 23 August 2011, he scored again and setting up a goal for MacDonald, in the second round of the Scottish League Cup, in a 4\u20133 loss against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]. However, his early season was overshadowed with a knee problem.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser doubtful for Bairns clash|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/09/22/417645-tidser-doubtful-for-bairns-clash/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nervous wait on injuries|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/09/28/417785-nervous-wait-on-injuries/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=28 September 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Following an operation, it was  announced that he will be out for two-months, he was expected to come back in December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Darren: I can fill gap left by Tids|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/10/15/418516-darren-i-can-fill-gap-left-by-tids/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=15 October 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Soon in mid-November, Tidser resumed training.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fouad's foot break agony|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/11/16/419758--fouads-foot-break-agony/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=16 November 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> Upon recovering from injury, Tidser spoke to the Greenock Telegraph describing his sidelined from injury as \"torture\" and hard to make a return.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser looking for return to action|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2011/12/10/420958-tidser-looking-for-return-to-action/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=10 December 2011|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In January 2012, after [[Stuart McCaffrey]] was ruled out for the season, Tidser was made Morton's team captain just after his 22nd birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/articles/2012/01/20/422540-tidser-named-new-morton-captain/|title=Tidser named new Morton captain|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=20 January 2012|accessdate=20 January 2012|first=Chris|last=Tait}}</ref> On 20 March 2012, he scored his second goal of the season, in a 2\u20130 win over Falkirk.\n\nIn 2012\u201313 season, Tidser had a good season with the club, having made a good display to compete with Partick Thistle to get promoted to Scottish Premier League, which Morton finished second. On 6 October 2012 Tidser provided a double assist for [[Kevin Rutkiewicz]] and [[Mark McLaughlin]], in a 3\u20131 win over Partick. It wasn't until 29 December 2012 when Tidser scored twice, in a 4\u20132 win over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]. That was followed up on 26 January 2013 when he scored in a 1\u20130 win over [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]. His next goal came on 23 February 2013 when he, again, scored against Dunfermline Athletic, with the same result on 29 December 2012. On 16 March 2013, Tidser scored his final goal of the season, in a 3\u20130 win over [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]. During the season, he also made a good display by making assists. He also scored five times in the Scottish Cup, including a brace against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] and [[Turriff United F.C.|Turriff United]], which was scored in the Scottish Cup replay. However, Tidser suffered an groin injury, that ruled him out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Missing training is a pain for Tidser|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/04/27/455259-missing-training-is-a-pain-for-tidser/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=27 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter a great season, Tidser was nominated for the [[2012\u201313 Scottish First Division|2012\u201313 First Division]] Player of the Year.<ref name=\"tids\"/> It got better for Tidser when he won the supporters' club awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terrace Talk: Fans' view|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/news/freecontent/articles/2013/04/30/455456-terrace-talk-fans-view/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, Tidser was the subject of a \u00a350k bid from [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]], which was rejected by Morton chairman [[Douglas Rae (businessman)|Douglas Rae]] at first.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/06/21/461753-50k-bid-for-tidser-rejected/|title=\u00a350k bid for Tidser rejected|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=21 June 2013|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref> Soon the bid was made again, but this time it was accepted five days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser set for Rotherham talks|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/06/26/462192-exclusive-tidser-set-for-rotherham-talks/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=26 June 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n===Rotherham United===\nTidser officially signed for [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 3 July 2013.<ref name=\"tidser\">{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2013/07/03/463034-breaking-news-tidser-signs-for-rotherham/|title=BREAKING NEWS: Tidser signs for Rotherham|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> The following week, on 9 July 2013, Tidser played against his former club Morton; when brought on, as a late substitute, he was given a standing ovation by Morton's fans.<ref>{{cite news|title=Greenock Morton 0\u20130 Rotherham United FT|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/greenock-morton-0-0-rotherham-united-ft-1-5838529|publisher=Sheffield Telegraph|date=9 July 2013|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter featuring on the bench in the first two matches of the opening game of the [[2013\u201314 Rotherham United F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Tidser finally made his debut after coming on as a late substitute in a 2\u20131 win over [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]]. However his start at Rotherham United didn't go as planned for him as his appearances had \"mostly have been off the bench\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Double boost for County|url=http://sport.bt.com/sportfootball/football/scottishfootball/scottishpremierleaguepreviews/double-boost-for-county-S11363864071883|publisher=BT Sports|date=3 January 2014|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2014, Tidser joined [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] on loan until the end of the 2013\u201314 season, in order to help the club retain their [[Scottish Premiership]] status next season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Triple Signing |url=http://www.rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk/news/triple-signing.aspx |publisher=rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103211619/http://www.rosscountyfootballclub.co.uk/news/triple-signing.aspx |archivedate=3 January 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser backs Ross County to win survival battle|url=http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Ross-County/Tidser-backs-Ross-County-to-win-survival-battle-09042014.htm|publisher=The Highland News|date=9 April 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser made his Ross County debut the next day, coming on as a substitute in the second half, in a 1\u20130 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross County 2\u20130 St Johnstone|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25532745|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 January 2014|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser's playing time increased, playing in midfielder position and assisted twice in two games against [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] on 15 February 2014 and [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 22 February 2014. However, his knee injury put Tidser out for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish Premiership briefing |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/article/26854/9291061/scottish-premiership-briefing |publisher=Sporting Life |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330130528/http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/article/26854/9291061/scottish-premiership-briefing |archivedate=30 March 2015 }}</ref> Tidser made 16 appearances for Ross County and returned to his parent club at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Summer shake-up on cards at Ross County|url=http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Ross-County/Summer-shake-up-on-cards-at-Ross-County-14052014.htm|publisher=Highland News|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter making his return to Rotherham United, Tidser made his first appearance in a year for the club, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] in [[2014\u201315 Football League Cup#First round|the first round of the League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham United 1\u20130 (aet) Fleetwood Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28652512|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Tidser made two more appearance for the club, against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in the league<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham United 0 \u2013 2 Watford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28749920|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> and another League Cup appearance against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Swansea City 1\u20130 Rotherham United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28847204|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> But on 1 September 2014, in the last hour of Deadline Day, Tidser signed for [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on loan until January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Latics Land Player on Deadline Day |url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20140901-michael-tidser-signs-1892201.aspx |publisher=Oldham Athletic A.F.C. |accessdate=1 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330131657/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/20140901-michael-tidser-signs-1892201.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> Tidser made his Oldham Athletic debut in [[2014\u201315 Football League Trophy#Northern section 2|the second round of Football League Trophy]], which they beat [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] 4\u20132 on penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oldham Athletic 2\u20132 (aet) (4\u20132 penalty shoot-out) Barnsley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29421215|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 February 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> However, Tidser struggled for the first team at the club and made seven appearance in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/loans-return-to-parent-clubs-2183169.aspx |title=Loans Return To Parent Clubs |publisher=Oldham Athletic A.F.C. |accessdate=30 March 2015 |date=6 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330134028/http://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/article/loans-return-to-parent-clubs-2183169.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\nHe was released in January 2015 after two years at Rotherham United, and was quickly on the radar of former club Morton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/01/13/521106-exclusive-morton-in-bid-for-tidser/|title=Morton in bid for Tidser|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themillers.co.uk/news/article/millers-agree-tidser-release-2192068.aspx |title=Millers agree Tidser release |publisher=Rotherham United F.C. |accessdate=30 March 2015 |date=9 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330131341/http://www.themillers.co.uk/news/article/millers-agree-tidser-release-2192068.aspx |archivedate=30 March 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n===Return to Morton===\n\nIn January 2015, Tidser returned to Morton on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/01/22/522196-breaking-tidser-seals-morton-return/|title=Tidser seals Morton return|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell|date=22 January 2015|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> He was unable, however, to play until the 2015\u201316 season due to [[FIFA]] transfer regulations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/greenock/articles/2015/01/23/522431-breaking-tidser-transfer-hits-red-tape/|title=Tidser transfer hits red tape|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|first=Jonathan|last=-Mitchell|date=23 January 2015|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> Because of this, Tidser played in the club's reserve matches, in order to maintain his fitness throughout the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidser stays sharp in Morton Under-20s|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/morton/articles/2015/03/20/528062-tidser-stays-sharp-in-morton-under20s/|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis 2015\u201316 season with Morton was limited to very few appearances before finally being ruled out all together in March after suffering a suspected [[hernia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/sport/14342008.Injured_Morton_star_s_season_could_be_over/|title=Injured Morton star's season could be over|publisher=Greenock Telegraph|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=15 March 2016|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Tidser signed a two-year extension with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gmfc.net/2017/06/08/tidser-signs-two-year-contract-extension/|title=Tidser signs two-year contract|publisher=Greenock Morton F.C.|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=8 June 2017|first=Jonathan|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nTidser made three appearances for both the Scotland [[Scotland national under-18 football team|under-18]] and [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] sides, scoring once for the under-18's against [[Turkey national under-18 football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=2492&playerID=39949&squadID=9|title=Michael Tidser|publisher=Scottish Football Association|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 4 November 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Greenock Morton F.C. season|2009\u201310]]<ref name=\"MT09\">{{soccerbase season|53238|2009|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]]\n|13||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Greenock Morton F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=\"MT10\">{{soccerbase season|53238|2010|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n|34||1||3||0||1||0||0||0||38||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Greenock Morton F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"MT11\">{{soccerbase 